EXPLANATION – Matter in bolded italics is new; matter between brackets [omitted material] is material to be omitted.
AN ACT relating to employment; revising provisions governing the
payment of wages and compensation to an employee who
resigns, quits or is discharged or placed on nonworking
status; revising the penalty imposed upon an employer for
the failure to pay such wages when due; and providing
other matters properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Under existing law, whenever an employer: (1) discharges an employee, the
2 wages and compensation earned and unpaid at the time of the discharge become
3 due and payable immediately; and (2) places an employee on nonworking status,
4 the wages earned and unpaid at the time the employee is placed on such status
5 become due and payable immediately. (NRS 608.020) Additionally, existing law
6 provides that whenever an employee resigns or quits his or her employment, the
7 wages and compensation earned and unpaid at the time of the employee’s
8 resignation or quitting are required to be paid not later than the day on which the
9 employee would have regularly been paid the wages or compensation or 7 days
10 after the employee resigns or quits, whichever is earlier. (NRS 608.030) Sections 1
11 and 2 of this bill revise those requirements with respect to compensation to instead
12 provide that any compensation of such an employee that is earned and unpaid at the
13 time the employee is discharged, resigns or quits is required to be paid in the same
14 manner and on the same day on which the employee would have regularly been
15 paid the compensation. Sections 1-3 of this bill define “compensation” to mean any
16 bonus, arrangement to share profits, fringe benefits, matching contribution made to
17 a plan authorized by 26 U.S.C. § 401(k) and any other similar contribution that an
18 employer has agreed to pay to an employee.
19 Existing law provides for the imposition of a penalty upon an employer who
20 fails to comply with the requirements pertaining to the payment of wages and
21 compensation of an employee who resigned, quit or was discharged or placed on
22 nonworking status. Under existing law, the wages or compensation of such an
